\cb3 Paper summary\cb1 \
\cb3 -------------\cb1 \
\cb3 The paper attempts to formalise the more or less folklore techniques known for making aggregate BLS signatures more efficient by adding extra public key components which make verification possible in G_1 and provide proofs of correctness for signatures that can be verified more efficiently. The authors propose a definition, prove the security of their scheme, and provide an implementation and benchmarks. Although I appreciate the effort is formalisation and implementation, there are a few issues with the formalisation and comparisons that make me believe the paper needs some work before it is publishable at a conference like FC.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Strengths and weaknesses\cb1 \
\cb3 ------------------------\cb1 \
\cb3 Strengths:\cb1 \
\cb3 - diagnosing and explaining the problem clearly\cb1 \
\cb3 - taking the right approach in formalising a set of folklore techniques\cb1 \
\cb3 - interesting techniques inc. extra public key components and DLEQ proofs\cb1 \
\cb3 - implementation in Rust and making it available\cb1 \
\cb3 - benchmarking\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Improvement needed:\cb1 \
\cb3 - not clear who does which verification (i.e. how is the proposed scheme used in practice by parties)\cb1 \
\cb3 - inconsistencies in the definitions (see below)\cb1 \
\cb3 - unfairness of the comparison (see below)\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Constructive feedback for authors\cb1 \
\cb3 ---------------------------------\cb1 \
\cb3 On Definition Inconsistencies\cb1 \
\
\cb3 The definition of Completeness for Aggregation uses the Verify algorithm with a single pk and a single signature (**), but the algorithm is defined earlier to take aggregated pks and signatures, so unless you define or require that AggregateKeys and AggregateSignatures return their input if n=1, the definition is not technically correct. This also allows you to state the previous paragraph unconditionally (where you say Perfect Completeness implies completeness of the underlying signature). This also defines an actual \'93underlying signature\'94 since with current definitions, the verification algorithm for a non-aggregated signature is unclear.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Considering three levels of adversary restrictions for the unforgeability security game:\cb1 \
\cb3 1. adversary needs to give all public keys and all signatures, challenger aggregates both and checks\cb1 \
\cb3 2. adversary needs to give all public keys and aggregated signature, challenger aggregates public keys and checks\cb1 \
\cb3 3. adversary needs to give aggregated public key and signature, challenger checks\cb1 \
\
\cb3 1 seems equivalent to individual unforgeability. 2 is your definition. 3 is the ideal intuitive case.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 The unforgeability definition assumes that aggregation is carried out honestly, but this is not necessarily the case in practice. In reality, an adversary that comes up with an apk and asig that verifies without knowledge of all the secret keys is a successful one. The current definition covers this attack only if AggregateKeys returns the list of keys (i.e. trivial aggregation). Besides, the given definition only covers static corruption, as opposed to the adversary seeing signatures first and then deciding to get access to secret keys, but I am not too worried about this latter issue as I think it would be possible to show that the two definitions are equivalent (although one would expect proper formal treatment to address this as well, at least intuitively).\cb1 \
\
\cb3 On the Scheme: why is the format of asig different when n=1 or n>1? Does this mean that for one signature DLEQ proof is checked, but for an aggregated signature they are not?\cb1 \
\
\cb3 On the Comparison\cb1 \
\
\cb3 To appropriately verify aggregate signatures, in a way that is comparable to aggregate BLS signatures, one needs to run AS.Verify (which verifies an asig against a pk_2 set) AND run AS.VerifyPoP which verifies pk_2 against pk_1, so I am not sure the comparison given in Table 1 is fair (what if some pk_2 is not valid?) as it seems to only cover the AS.Verify time for AS.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Could you also comment on whether comparison with [7] needs to be considered or not, and why?\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Typos and other minor issues:\cb1 \
\cb3 - p2: groupslike\cb1 \
\cb3 - p3: define PoP\cb1 \
\cb3 - p3: if you define AS=(tuple of algorithms) then you don\'92t need to repeat the whole tuple every single time\cb1 \
\
