\cb3 Paper summary\cb1 \
\cb3 -------------\cb1 \
\cb3 This paper presents several optimizations to improve the pairing-based multisignature schemes. First, the paper illustrates that verifying partial signatures using the Chaum-Pedersen Sigma-protocol for proving the discrete-logarithm equality (DLEQ) relation is more efficient than using bilinear pairings. Then, the paper presents optimization, which lets the signers compute the signature in G1 while ensuring that the verifier only needs to perform n group operations in G1.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Strengths and weaknesses\cb1 \
\cb3 ------------------------\cb1 \
\cb3 Strengths:\cb1 \
\cb3 - The paper is timely and tries to ground some of the folklore optimizations regarding BLS signatures formally.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Weakness:\cb1 \
\cb3 - With this scheme, the aggregated signatures are larger. The paper should make it more explicit.\cb1 \
\cb3 - Requires additional evaluations.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Constructive feedback for authors\cb1 \
\cb3 ---------------------------------\cb1 \
\cb3 1. A drawback of the proposed scheme is that the aggregated signature is now larger, as the signature now consists of one group element from both G1 and G2. I recommend making this limitation explicit and mentioning it upfront.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 2. Currently, authors compare their optimized signature scheme with the BLS multisignature scheme, where the public keys are in G2 and signatures are in G1 (also known as the minSig variant). I recommend authors compare their optimizations with the BLS multisignature variant with public keys in G1 and signatures in G2 (also known as the minPk variant). Moreover, authors should compare with minPk variant + Chaum-Pedersen DLEQ instead of pairing (say Variant-3).\cb1 \
\
\cb3 I believe comparing the proposed scheme with the minPk variant, and Variant-3 is essential for the complete picture, as each of these variants has its advantages and disadvantages.\cb1 \
\
\
\cb3 * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *\cb1 \
