\cb3 Paper summary\cb1 \
\cb3 -------------\cb1 \
\cb3 The authors observe that nowadays mostly type 3 pairing curves are used with slower arithmetic and hash-to-curve operations in the second source group as they are defined over an extension field. They then present optimisations for the usage of BLS signatures in large distributed systems. The authors propose: (1) to give the public key in both source groups ; (2) that aggregated signatures should have the aggregated public key in the second source group, so that checks are done mainly in the first source group; (3) that non-aggregated signatures should carry Chaum-Pedersen style proofs of discrete log equality in the first source group, so that they can be verified without using pairings. They use a proof-of-possession to check the correctness of the key.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Strengths and weaknesses\cb1 \
\cb3 ------------------------\cb1 \
\cb3 Strengths:\cb1 \
\cb3 - BLS signatures are important in practice\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Weaknesses:\cb1 \
\cb3 - notations such as 
